meaning: n.共和党人adj.共和党的共和的           The United States has a republican form of government.美国政府是共和制的。      来自 republic, 共和.共和国的n.共和党人[-an表名词和形容词""…地方,...人] a.共和的He is a member of the Republican Party.他是共和党的一员.      noun [ C ]uk/rɪˈpʌb.lɪ.kən/ us/rəˈpʌb.lɪ.kən/   a supporter of government by elected representatives of the people rather than government by a king or queen拥护共和政体者；共和主义者  adjectiveuk/rɪˈpʌb.lɪ.kən/ us/rəˈpʌb.lɪ.kən/   relating to a republic共和国的；共和政体的 a republican system of government共和政体  noun [ C ]uk/rɪˈpʌb.lɪ.kən/ us/rəˈpʌb.lɪ.kən/ written abbreviation Rep.  a member of the Republican Party in the US美国共和党党员 a person who believes that Northern Ireland belongs to the Irish Republic北爱尔兰共和主义者       A Republican is a member of one of the two major political parties in the United States. George W. Bush, the forty-fourth US president, is a Republican.Use the word Republican — with a capital R — when you're talking about a member of the more conservative of the main political groups in the US. Republicans are known for their conservative views on economic and social issues, as well as policies that reduce taxes and government services. If you spell the word with a lower-case r, it simply means someone who believes in a government by the people and their elected representatives.The adjective republican describes a government made up of representatives who are elected by the citizens. If you live in the United States, you’re part of a republican system of government.In a republican government, citizens have a lot of power — their vote determines who is running the government. The word republican has a noun and an adjective form. The noun is for a person who supports that style of government, and the adjective describes something with those characteristics. But if you see republican with a capital letter “r” — “Republican ” — then that refers to a specific type of republican, one who’s a member of the Republican Party.republican: republicanism, republicanly, republicans/republic: republican, republics/republicanism: republicanisms    Republican

You might describe your Egyptian pen pal as an Arab.Whether someone describes himself as an Arab — rather than a Persian or Kurd, for example — has to do with his language, culture, where he lives, and his ancestors. Someone who lives in Yemen is likely to call herself an Arab, while a Moroccan might consider herself to be a Berber. It is much safer, and less likely to cause offense, to describe people by the countries they're from. ClarkH·克拉克牧师大人       Use the noun reverend to talk about a clergy member of a Christian church, as in: ""Let's ask the reverend if she'll marry us next week.""A minister, preacher, or priest can each also be called a reverend. The word is often capitalized, especially when it's used in the form ""the Reverend so-and-so.""
